 ISMARA'S DOOM
A Chronicle of the Parks Group

CHAPTER ONE: THE CITY OF STONE

PART I: THIRTY MINUTES, THEN BUSINESS
The cart smelled like old furs and road dust and, increasingly, like the inside of a glacier.
This last quality was new. It had developed over three days of travel south from Winterhold, accumulating in the canvas and the wool and the gaps between the floorboards the way cold accumulates in stone — slowly, thoroughly, until you stopped noticing it and started assuming it was simply what the world felt like now. A thin rime of frost had crystallized along the interior roof. Bjorn had not commented on this. Bjorn was a man who had learned, somewhere in sixty-odd years of practical life, that some things were better addressed by not addressing them.
Ismara sat in the cargo space with the stillness of something that had been still for a very long time and found no particular reason to change. She had been writing when they set out that morning. She was writing now. The notebook was small and the pages were dense and the notation she filled them with was angular and precise in a way that bore no resemblance to any alphabet Y'droj the Argonian had encountered in thirty years of attentive travel. He had been watching her write for three days. He was not closer to understanding it.
What he understood: she was cold, in the way that old stone is cold rather than the way that winter is cold. She communicated by writing. She had said perhaps forty words since Winterhold, and none of them had been sorry or you're welcome or any of the words that usually cushioned the space between people traveling together. She watched [Khajiit Name] with a quality of attention he could not yet name — not warmly, not coldly, but with the complete focused reception of someone for whom all incoming data was immediately sorted and filed.
[Khajiit Name] had both hands wrapped against the cold of the cart. The rotjoint had been worse since Frostmere — the swelling around the knuckles, the stiffness, the geometric scarring that had appeared in the weeks since in patterns that the healers at Winterhold had looked at and then looked away from, as if extended examination might require them to have an explanation. She flexed her right hand now and watched Windhelm rise from the frozen landscape through a gap in the canvas.
Dark stone. Stormcloak blue on the towers. Coal smoke against a grey sky. A bridge and a gate checkpoint, two guards visible at this distance as shapes.
Bjorn stopped the cart.
The problem was the guards. The guards checked what came through, and Ismara was — the word the party had settled on was unusual, which was doing considerable work. She was visibly not warm. She generated a cold that had nothing to do with the weather. The Ice Crown on her head was not something that invited casual explanation.
[Khajiit Name] asked her to wait in the cart.
Ismara looked at her. Then she reached for her notebook with the unhurried deliberateness of someone for whom thirty additional minutes was, in any meaningful scale, unremarkable. She wrote four words and turned the notebook around.
Thirty minutes. Then business.
She put the notebook away. She arranged herself among the furs and the cargo and was still.
[Wood Elf Name] was watching the place where Ismara had been. She watched it for a moment longer than necessary, with the focused quiet of someone who has seen the corner of something and is deciding whether to look at the rest of it.
"She knows where we're going," she said.
"She knows where she's going," Y'droj said. He opened his notebook. "That is a different thing."
Bjorn clicked his tongue at Mable. The cart rolled toward the gate.

PART II: HROLF STONE-FIST
The younger guard recognized them before the cart had fully stopped.
"Wait —" Not a challenge, an exclamation. He had the broad open face of someone for whom enthusiasm came first and caution arrived later, if at all. "You're them. The Frostmere lot — my cousin serves in Jarl Korir's guard, he wrote about you. Said you walked right into that barrow. Said the cold stopped the next morning."
"It did," Y'droj said.
Hrolf Stone-Fist waved them through with a grin and fell into step beside them as they crossed the bridge, talking about his cousin and the barrow and how Windhelm needed capable people, there had been disappearances near the Hall of the Dead, three people gone, grinding sounds from below the building that Helgrid the healer had reported to the guard weeks ago and nobody had come —
He stopped. They had come out of the bridge's stone throat into the city, and Windhelm had a smell — coal and fish and old stone and something underneath those things that was harder to locate. The quality of a place that had been frightened long enough that the fear had become part of the atmosphere.
Hrolf told them the temple was north. He told them to keep their weapons sheathed. He told them, as they walked, that they should avoid the Gray Quarter if they could help it. The Dunmer. You understand how it is. Windhelm men, they had certain ways —
[Wood Elf Name] had very still eyes when she was deciding something. Whatever she was deciding, she decided not to say it.
Y'droj said: "The temple."
Hrolf pointed. They followed.
At the end of an alley to their left, a Dunmer woman stood in a doorway watching them pass with the practiced attention of someone who had spent years calibrating the difference between a threat and a stranger passing through. Y'droj looked back at her once. She did not look away.
[Wood Elf Name] had already looked back. She looked back a second time.

PART III: WHAT HELGRID NOTICED
The Temple of Arkay had been renamed, by popular consensus, the Temple of Talos. The priests objected. Windhelm did not listen. Helgrid, the senior healer, had stopped correcting anyone approximately a decade ago and redirected the energy toward medicine, which at least produced results.
She examined [Khajiit Name]'s hands with the thorough unhurried attention of a woman who gathered information before she formed language around it. The joint swelling. The stiffness. The geometric scarring in the tissue — angular, precise, repeating in ways that scar tissue did not generally repeat, in patterns that, if you followed them far enough, seemed to be going somewhere.
The room was quiet while she worked. On a cot in the corner, Bered — a dockworker, brought in by Hrolf that morning — lay with one arm bare despite the cold. The marks on his arm were angular and precise and faintly luminous, blue-white, coming from somewhere inside the tissue rather than sitting on top of it.
Helgrid had looked at Bered's arm first. Then at [Khajiit Name]'s hands.
She had not said anything for a moment.
Now she set down the hand she was holding and picked up the other one.
"The inflammation," she said. "Rotjoint spreads outward from the joint capsule. This is the reverse."
"I contracted it fighting a Draugr," [Khajiit Name] said. "At Frostmere Barrow."
"The inflammation pattern is consistent with Rotjoint." Helgrid turned the hand over. She traced the geometric scarring with one careful finger. "The scarring is not. This began somewhere else. The joint reacted to it."
She set the hand down. She picked up her quill.
"I can manage the pain. There is a formula — Quintus Navale, in the Gray Quarter. He compounds the salve." She wrote it on a strip of parchment and handed it over and did not add: the pattern in this scarring and the marks on Bered's arm use the same system. She did not add it because the Friar was arriving, and because some observations needed more information before they became statements, and because she was a professional.
The Friar was a broad man with the institutional competence of someone who had handled crises before and preferred to do so quietly. He examined Bered. He looked at the marks. He looked at Hrolf, who said: Frostmere. They handled it. He looked at the party.
"Eight hundred gold," he said. "From the temple coffers. Find out what's causing this. Stop the disappearances." A gravedigger. A beggar. A drifter who had been sleeping near the Hall of the Dead. All in the past month. "Nobody has come."
On the cot, Bered said: "It didn't hurt. As much as I thought it would."
He said it with the distant confusion of a man braced for a pain that had arrived differently than expected and who could not stop trying to account for the gap.
They took the contract. Eight hundred gold. They went to find the docks.

PART IV: THE DOCKS
Azarain ran the docks on practical logic — twenty years of it, with forearms to match — and he told them about the woman without being asked because the woman was the thing that hadn't fit.
Strange. In the shadows mostly. Extraordinarily attractive in a way that produced discomfort before the eye had finished looking. A Khajiit dockworker — Dar-Ma, fifteen years on the water, good worker — had spoken to her one evening near the east cargo berth. Had turned to a colleague afterward and said he wasn't feeling well. Had gone home. The Dunmer worker — Bered, yes, the one from the temple — had spoken to her the next day.
Y'droj asked whether she had touched either of them.
Azarain thought about it. "The Khajiit. On the shoulder. In passing. Like she knew him."
Y'droj wrote it down and drew a box around it.
[Wood Elf Name] asked: "Did she touch anyone else? Anyone you haven't mentioned yet?"
Azarain thought again, longer this time. He named two more. A laborer. A woman who loaded cargo on the south berth. He hadn't connected them. He hadn't known there was anything to connect.
[Wood Elf Name] looked at Y'droj. Y'droj was already writing.

PART V: THE APOTHECARY
Quintus Navale's shop in the Gray Quarter had the smell of a workspace used seriously — dried herbs, alchemical cleanness, and underneath it the warm human smell of a home. Quintus was a compact Imperial man with the professional manner of someone accustomed to confidentiality. It took twenty minutes of careful conversation to establish that Dar-Ma was upstairs.
Hiding. Because Khajiit did not live inside Windhelm's walls — that was the rule, the unspoken absolute — and because Quintus and Dar-Ma were, quietly, in love, and the life they had built in the space above the apothecary required not being noticed.
Quintus told them about the salve, mixed prescriptions, held himself together with the focused activity of a man who had decided that doing the next useful thing was the only alternative to not doing it. He did not mention Dar-Ma until they already knew to ask.
Upstairs, Dar-Ma could not speak. The geometric marks covered his arms and were spreading toward his chest — angular, precise, layering over each other in configurations that looked less like scarring and more like something being written. His eyes found [Khajiit Name] when she entered the room. They stayed on her. He could not turn his head.
They went back downstairs and told Quintus they would try.
Quintus said nothing. He had the face of a man who had decided that try was the only word available and was holding it carefully.

PART VI: THE HOUSE OF CURIOSITIES
Calixto Vividius's shop was the kind of place that made you work to find what was wrong with it. Taxidermied things in glass cases. Too many candles. Bone-and-wire amulets hanging from the ceiling with the nonchalance of a man who found necromantic theory interesting and saw no reason to be discreet about it.
Calixto was warm. Curious. Delighted to meet the people who had handled Frostmere — what a remarkable thing, please, come in —
He saw [Khajiit Name]'s hands.
His eyes went to them and stayed. One beat. Two.
"Where," he said — the warmth dialing down to something more precise — "did you get those marks?"
Draugr fight, [Khajiit Name] said. Frostmere.
"Of course," Calixto said. "Yes. A Draugr fight. Naturally."
[Wood Elf Name] watched his face when he said it. She watched it the way she watched things she was not yet ready to name — with the patient attention of someone waiting for a pattern to complete itself.
He was the only person they had spoken to all day who had accepted this explanation without hesitation.
Y'droj put a small mark in his notebook. [Wood Elf Name] said nothing, which in her particular register meant she had already put the same mark somewhere internal.
The conversation degraded. Calixto grew evasive about the journal and its Atmoran notation, proprietary in a way that had nothing to do with the price he was asking. He grew agitated about the marks in ways he worked to conceal. And then, apparently having taken their measure, he looked at [Khajiit Name] and said —
Oblique. Acid. Dressing itself as observation.
"You're a load-bearing wall, aren't you. Structurally integral. I imagine that comes with all sorts of interesting complications."
He knew what the marks meant. He understood exactly what he was saying. He said it anyway, to watch what happened.
What happened was [Khajiit Name]'s claws.
"How," she said, very quietly, "do you know what those marks mean."
Calixto screamed for the guards.

Hrolf Stone-Fist arrived at a jog with two guards at his back. He looked at [Khajiit Name]. He looked at Calixto pressed against his own display case. He looked at the shelves — the amulets, the soul gem fragments, the materials of a man conducting research he had not been asked about and had not reported. His eyes stayed on the shelves one beat longer than necessary.
When Calixto saw Hrolf in the doorway, his expression did something that was not relief.
[Wood Elf Name] caught it. She touched Y'droj's arm, once, briefly. He had caught it too.
Outside on the street, Hrolf suggested the Palace of the Kings. Brunwulf Free-Winter. The court wizard. "Wulfgar — can't use magic, never could, but nobody in Windhelm knows the Atmorans better."
Behind them, through the shop window, Calixto watched them go.

PART VII: THE GLUTTON AND THE SCHOLAR
Galmar Stone-Fist was eating lunch when they arrived at the Palace of the Kings, eating with the focused energy of a man who had scheduled this hour and resented its interruption. He directed them to Wulfgar. He offered the gold they already had. He returned to his food.
[Wood Elf Name] watched him until they turned the corner.
"He's just hungry," Y'droj said.
"I know," she said. "I'm still watching."

Wulfgar did not hear them enter.
He was at the bottom of forty years of Atmoran scholarship — scrolls, stone rubbings, annotated maps, the accumulated product of a lifetime spent caring deeply about something nobody else had bothered to care about. He was the only man in Windhelm who had taught himself to read Atmoran notation from first principles, in the complete absence of external encouragement, because it interested him.
Y'droj said his name.
Wulfgar surfaced.
He translated what he could of the journal with the speed of genuine fluency. Nodes. Structural anchors. A working distributed across geography. He looked at [Khajiit Name]'s hands with the excitement of a man who has found a primary source walking through his door. The marks indicate a component of the larger working. Not incidental. Integral. Load-bearing.
The negotiation took twenty minutes. Wulfgar wanted five thousand gold. Y'droj and [Wood Elf Name] spoke briefly, quietly, in the way of people who have divided the labour between them and each knows their role — Y'droj held the number at two thousand; [Wood Elf Name] held Wulfgar's attention, asked questions about his research, made the man feel that what he was being offered was not just gold but an audience that understood the value of what he had spent forty years building. Together they arrived at two thousand gold and the journal.
Wulfgar pulled a piece of calf-skin from his collection — a rubbing from one of the earlier victims, something he had been working on separately. He laid it beside his transcription of [Khajiit Name]'s markings.
"Two different hands," he said. "Look. Here —" he indicated the rubbing "— someone writing Atmoran notation who does not read Atmoran notation. The shapes are correct. The logic is not. Like a child writing down words they have heard spoken but never seen written."
He moved to the transcription.
"This is fluent. The grammatical structures are archaic — predates my oldest reference by at least three thousand years. Whoever wrote this has been writing in this language for a very long time." He leaned closer. Something shifted in his expression. "And these accent marks."
He pointed.
Small. Angular in the way that Atmoran notation was angular — hard geometric lines, built for permanence. Except at the top of each one, where the line curved back on itself. Twice. Symmetrically.
[Wood Elf Name] said: "Those are hearts."
The word landed in the room with the specific weight of a correct answer.
Wulfgar looked at his transcription. He looked at [Wood Elf Name]. He looked back at his transcription.
"The accent marks," he said, carefully, "are hearts. Yes. Archaic notation, native fluency, three thousand years older than my oldest reference — and the accent marks are small decorative hearts. In multiple places. Throughout the formula."
He looked up.
"I don't know what to make of that."
Y'droj looked at his notebook. He had been recording Wulfgar's translation with methodical precision — the nodes, the anchors, the structural integrity of [Khajiit Name]'s position in the working. He looked at all of it. He looked at the hearts.
He looked at [Wood Elf Name].
She was already looking at [Khajiit Name].
[Khajiit Name] was looking at the transcription with the expression of a woman receiving information that was landing in more than one place at once and had not yet decided what to do with any of it.
Y'droj wrote, very carefully, in the margin of his notebook: Personal. Specific. Not industrial.
He did not show it to anyone. But when [Wood Elf Name] glanced over his shoulder and read it, she gave a single small nod, and that was enough.

PART VIII: BUSINESS
They got back to the cart as the last light left the sky.
Ismara was standing outside it. Still, patient, in the long blue dusk — and when [Khajiit Name] came close enough, she turned with the unhurried attention of someone who had registered the arrival some time ago and simply waited for it to reach her.
She opened her notebook and wrote without preamble:
Where have you been.
Not a question. An accounting.
[Khajiit Name] told her. The investigation. The dockworker crystallizing above the apothecary while his lover compounded prescriptions downstairs. The healer who had noticed something she could not explain. The collector who had known what the marks meant and screamed for guards when asked how. The court scholar who had found, in the accent marks of a formula older than anything in his collection, small decorative hearts.
Ismara listened with the absolute, complete attention she brought to all incoming information. She looked at [Khajiit Name] throughout.
When the account was finished she wrote two lines:
I would like to visit the catacombs beneath this city.
Tomorrow. Will you take me.
"Tomorrow," [Khajiit Name] said.
Ismara put the notebook away and folded herself back into the cart. The matter was settled.
They slept in the cart that night to save money. Bjorn smoked his pipe on the bench. Mable stood patient in her traces.
In the dark, Y'droj lay with his notebook open on his chest and listened to the frost form on the canvas. Beside him, [Wood Elf Name] was awake too — he could tell by the quality of her stillness, the particular kind of not-sleeping that came from a mind that had not finished with the day's material.
"The two handwriting styles," he said quietly.
"Yes," she said.
"And the woman on the docks. Touching people. In passing."
"Yes."
A silence. Outside, Windhelm settled into its nightly routines of shuttered windows and brazier-light.
"The hearts," Y'droj said.
[Wood Elf Name] didn't answer for a moment. Then: "Someone put someone specific into a four-thousand-year-old formula and signed it."
Y'droj looked at the frost on the canvas. He looked at the ceiling of the cart for a long time.
"That is one way to describe it," he said.
Neither of them slept for a while.
In the corner of the cart, nearly invisible beneath the furs, something turned a page. The writing continued.
Outside, Windhelm breathed its cold breath, and in the temple on the north side of the market, Bered lay on his cot with his eyes open and said, to no one: it didn't hurt. As much as I thought.


